column18: 11/17/2003: Protestors turned violent in Buan, South Korea, resulting in the injury of 60 police officers and protestors. The protest was in response to a planned nuclear waste dump for the area.
column64: The protestors wanted to keep a nuclear waste dump out of their area.
column97: The protestors used farm equipment, steel pipes, homemade incendiary devices and threw fermented shrimp at the riot police.

column18: 05/20/2006: Perpetrator, Ji Choong-ho attacked the chairwoman of the main opposition Grand National Party, Park Geun-Hye, with a box cutter knife as she was campaigning in Seoul, South Korea. Park suffered a ten-centimeter cut on her face that required sixty stitches. Ji reportedly stated that he performed this action to �save democracy.�
column39: Grand National Party Chairwoman Park Geun-Hye
column97: A box-cutter knife was used in the attack.
column125: Park was not only the chairwoman of the main opposition party in South Korea, she was also one of the leading candidates for the 2007 presidential elections and the daughter of former President Park Chung Hee, who was an authoratarian leader of the nation from 1961 to 1979.  There were two other suspects, but police stated that they believed Ji worked alone.  It also said that Ji was to be indicted for attempted murder on June 8 or 9, 2006.

column18: 2/3/2001: A bomb hidden in a briefcase was discovered outside of the Civil Stadium in Taegu, Yeongnam, South Korea.  Two individuals driving by spotted the briefcase, brought it into their van, and tried opening it.  The briefcase exploded, causing minor injuries to both individuals.  No group has claimed responsibility for the device.
